This guy @dt_chain just bought a #CryptoPunk NFT for 8,000 Ethereum, which is $23.3 million dollars.ğŸ¤¯

I'm really curious as to why? https://t.co/EDgz64Kg4n

Artists, please don't repeat the same mistakes that artists have made again & again throughout history. As they say OWN YOUR MUSIC. 

If you want to share $ w/ your fans, that's amazing, but you can't determine how that's done or how much if you don't own the rights! ğŸ˜„

Lastly, FULL commercial rights in the hands of the wrong people (who are not educated in the music space) can really mess things up & cause major headaches in terms of the administrative work that comes from registering/collecting from different revenue generating entities.

Third, giving away FULL commercial rights does not build a healthy community around an artist. It's about control over the artist's work. I want my community to be partners, supporters, listeners, true fans - not my owners.

Second, it's only right that artists get to determine how their music is used & monetized, (or not). 

Giving up FULL commercial rights opens up the chance that anyone can legally use your music w/ imagery that goes against your morals and values...AND profit from it.

First reason, because artists should be the OWNERS of their work/copyrights. Not NFT holders or anyone else. 

Giving away FULL commercial rights will re-create the issues around artists losing control and being slaves of the record labels. Please, not in Web 3.

As an artist, I WILL incentivize my music NFT holders through participation of future royalties, partial commercial rights, and other great incentives in the future. However, I will choose to NEVER give away FULL commercial rights or copyrights to my musical works
